ce:section.ce:para:
The phenomena of both mono-emission and multi-emission are observed when checking the samples of PEPA-CDs in PVA matrix (Fig. S3, Fig. 2
                        ). We believe that EDF spectra of multi-emission are more characteristic and effective in anti-counterfeiting identification, and, therefore, pay more attention to it in the following sections. Based on our data, it is verified that the occurrence of multi-emission has a close relationship with the concentration of CDs in PVA film. At the concentration of 30 wt%, the EDF spectra show a mono-emission band at about 440 nm. While, with the increasing of concentration of CDs, another emission band at about 525 nm emerges and gradually increases. Similar phenomena of multi-emission of CDs in solution have been observed previously [13–18]. At present, there are two different viewpoints on the multi-emission behaviors of CDs in solution: (i) the two bands arise from the carbon core and its surface domain, respectively; and (ii) the bands result from different kinds of aggregates of functional groups of CDs. Because the former proposal cannot explain the concentration-dependent FL behavior, we believe the latter one is a plausible mechanism to explain our observed results. Based this mechanism, for our solid samples, it is plausible that different kinds of aggregates are formed at different concentrations of CDs in PVA film, consequently give rise to two FL centers at suitable concentrations. In order to get a better insight into this result, we studied samples of PEPA-CDs in PVA aqueous solution, and similar phenomenon of multi-emission can be detected (Fig. 3
                        ). However, the intensity of emission band at 525 nm in aqueous solution is much higher than that in PVA matrix; the difference between the samples may be due to the presence of water [3,27]. Anyway, for application purposes, it is certain that EDF spectra with multi-emission offer some advantages for anti-counterfeiting, such as easy identification and hard duplication, owing to the large excitation-dependent spectral shift and special feature of EDF curves.
